{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504255","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504255"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:13:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:13:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2310"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2310"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.13,0.54,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2310"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111258"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2310","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2310"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2310"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93390"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"688"},{"type":"contributions","id":"698"},{"type":"contributions","id":"710"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12786"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15888"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36813"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42468"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43123"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45110"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111258"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 80-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for an annual diabetes and kidney health review. She reports no symptoms. She has type 2 diabetes diagnosed eight years ago and no other significant medical history. She takes metformin and does not take any other regular medications. She is independent with activities of daily living, walks daily, has had no recent travel, and does not use substances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 135/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Body mass index is 24 kg/m\u00b2. Cardiovascular, respiratory and neurological examinations are unremarkable. Foot inspection and monofilament testing are normal. Fundoscopy shows no retinopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EGlycated haemoglobin 7.0% (4.0-5.9)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EEstimated glomerular filtration rate 54 mL/min/1.73 m\u00b2 (\u226590)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EUrine albumin:creatinine ratio 15 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;3.5)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESerum potassium 4.6 mmol/L (3.5-5.2)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESerum creatinine 92 \u00b5mol/L (45-90)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Initiate sulfonylurea therapy","Increase metformin dose","Initiate an angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor","Provide lifestyle advice for weight loss","Initiate statin therapy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDiabetes-related chronic kidney disease is characterised by reduced estimated glomerular filtration rate and/or albuminuria. Early kidney-protective therapy is a priority in primary care. Renin-angiotensin system blockade with an angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor or angiotensin receptor blocker reduces albuminuria, slows estimated glomerular filtration rate decline, and lowers kidney and cardiovascular risk. Guidance from Australian kidney and primary care organisations supports initiation when albuminuria is present, including when baseline blood pressure is below conventional thresholds, with follow-up checks of creatinine and potassium one to two weeks after initiation and dose changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitiate an angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor\u003C/strong\u003E is the best next step because this older woman has diabetes, stage 3a chronic kidney disease (estimated glomerular filtration rate 54 mL/min/1.73 m\u00b2), and confirmed albuminuria (urine albumin:creatinine ratio 15 mg/mmol). Renin-angiotensin system blockade reduces albuminuria and slows progression irrespective of her baseline blood pressure of 135/70 mmHg. In older adults, titration should be individualised, with monitoring of creatinine and potassium within one to two weeks of initiation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease metformin dose\u003C/strong\u003E may improve glycaemic control, but does not target albuminuria or kidney disease progression. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitiate sulfonylurea therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not preferred for kidney protection and increases hypoglycaemia risk in older adults. When additional glucose lowering is needed, consider agents with kidney and cardiovascular benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProvide lifestyle advice for weight loss\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary here given a body mass index of 24 kg/m\u00b2 and, while healthy lifestyle advice is always valuable, it does not replace renin-angiotensin system blockade for albuminuria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInitiate statin therapy\u003C/strong\u003E lowers cardiovascular risk and is appropriate for many older adults with diabetes, but it does not reduce albuminuria or slow kidney decline to the same extent; the kidney-specific priority is starting an angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["In adults with diabetes and persistent albuminuria, start a renin-angiotensin system blocker for kidney protection irrespective of baseline blood pressure.","An angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitor or angiotensin receptor blocker reduces albuminuria and slows estimated glomerular filtration rate decline in diabetic kidney disease.","Blood pressure targets and therapy intensity should be individualised in older adults to balance kidney and cardiovascular benefit against risks such as hypotension and falls."],"references":["Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) Management in Primary Care (5th edition). Kidney Health Australia, Melbourne, 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93390"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2310"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93390","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93390"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-11T21:00:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-11T21:00:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2310"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111258"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":n